Course Diary, Chapter 1

Elizabeth Oakes

https://github.com/Eilif/IODS-project

My second Ph.D. supervisor, Dr. Turo Hiltunen, recommended the course to me. I come from an English philology background, but in my research, I take a computational approach to style in New Wave science fiction. The research generates a moderate amount of numerical data.

From this course, I hope to gain:

  1. a clear idea of ways I can effectively make the data open access

  2. an understanding of basic statistical processes and tools

Statistics aren’t necessary for my core line of inquiry, but I suspect having the tools to hand would enable asking some interesting questions when comparing data from two or more text types within a corpus.

Two years ago during my master’s studies, I took a course on statistics for linguists with R. I haven’t really played with R since, so I am rusty. I do remember basic concepts from statistics and the details of common tests like T-test and Chi-squared. I suppose where I struggle is in understanding how to apply these in a relevant way to my data. If I remember, T-test, for example, needs an expected value. But what would be the expected frequency of prepositions of movement in a fiction text? Frankly, answers I’ve gotten to questions like that (or cooked up myself) tend to sound more than a little hand-wavey.

I’m not sure this course can directly help me with this issue, but I’m hoping it will give me the perspective to think about it more clearly.

Course Diary, Chapter 2

Analyzing data and making it pretty

Elizabeth Oakes, 11.11.2019

This analysis looks at data that characterizes the learning of a set of students. There are seven variables related to learning (gender, age, attitude, deep learning, strategic learning, surface learning, and points) and 166 observations of these variables.

The data has already been wrangled, so once imported, plotting can begin immediately.

Comparing each variable to each other variable gives a broad overview of the data. It is possible to see in the visualization that increase in age seems to have a positive relationship with strategic learning, but a negative relationship with surface learning. However, the correlation coefficients are far from 1 or -1 respectively. It’s hard to glean from the visualization, but a correlation coefficient of -0.324 suggests that deep learning decreases as surface learning increases. Additionally, as attitude increases, so do points, visible both in the scatterplot and in the correlation coefficient of 0.437. Finally, strategic learning may have a positive relationship with points and surface learning a negative relationship. From the overview, these appear to be the most interesting relationships to explore.

An overview of each variable’s relation to the next.

The positive relationship between attitude and points looks to be strongest in this data set. Graphing these two variables by gender reveals a clear improvement in points that pairs with an improved attitude. The effect appears slightly stronger in males than females, but especially considering the smallish number of observations in this variable, significance is unlikely.

Attitude in relation to exam points.

Removing gender from the plot yields a clearer view. Here the regression line shows that a better attitude towards learning leads to higher scores on exams regardless of gender.

An overview of each variable’s relation to the next.

The next strongest relationship is the negative one between deep and surface learning. Creating a scatterplot of these two variable by gender reveals that there seems to be no effet for female students. For male students on the other hand, there is a strong tendency for deep learning to decrease as surface learning increases.

Deep and surface learning by gender.

Here is where I should handle part 5 of the analysis assignment to produce the following diagnostic plots: Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage. But I have had a long and exhausting week, so I will study it on my own time and not include it here. Evaluators: Please -2 or 3 points. Without those further analyses, I think I can say that the assumption that attitude correlates to performance is intuitively appealing, but the reality might be less clear. For example, in the over all analysis there appears to be a positive relationship between age and attitude. So, the older you are, the better your attitude towards learning, the better your exam scores. Do those exam scores really come from a good attitude, or does age confer other benefits, such as familiarity with the mechanics of exam taking or broad knowledge that supports even specialized tasks? Clearly there is a lot to explore in this data set.

Student Alcohol Consumption and Regression Analysis

Elizabeth Oakes, 17.11.2019

We have a dataset of survey answers from Portuguese high school students. There are 382 observations of 36 variables, as follows.

colnames(alc) “X” “school” “sex” “age” “address” “famsize” “Pstatus”
“Medu” “Fedu” “Mjob” “Fjob” “reason” “nursery” “internet”
“guardian” “traveltime” “studytime” “failures” “schoolsup” “famsup” “paid”
“activities” “higher” “romantic” “famrel” “freetime” “goout” “Dalc”
“Walc” “health” “absences” “G1” “G2” “G3” “alc_use”
“high_use”

“X” is a kind of index, “Dalc” weekday alcohol use, “Walc” weekend alcohol use, “G1-3” records grades in math and Portuguese classes, and “high_use” is a logical variable denoting whether a student exceeds a certain level of alcohol consumption.

Let’s view observations of each variable graphically by using the code: gather(alc) %>% ggplot(aes(value)) + facet_wrap(“key”, scales = “free”) + geom_bar()

Fig. 1 An overview of each variable.

From this overview, I pick four variables and explore their possible relation to high alcohol use, romantic (student has a romantic relationship), freetime (how much free time does the student have), goout (how often does the student go out with friends), and G3 (student’s final grade in their course - math or Portuguese).

I hypothesize that having a romantic relationship reduces the likelihood of high alcohol consumption because the student will dedicate time to the relationship that might otherwise be spent partying. Free time and going out with friends, however, may increase the likelihood of high alcohol consumption, especially the latter variable. From another angle, what kind of effect does high alcohol consumption have on grades? I don’t think it has the biggest effect on grades, but I’m curious if there is one.

Let’s begin by visualizing the relationship between final course grade and high alcohol use by sex using the folling code.

g1 <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = high_use, y = G3, col = sex)) g1 + geom_boxplot() + ylab(“grade”) + ggtitle(“Student grades by alcohol consumption and sex”)

Fig. 2

It appears that the mean grade for female students is not much affected by high alcohol use, but it does correlate with a lowered mean grade for male students.

Is alcohol use affected by going out with friends or having a romantic relationship? Lets visualize those relationships in sequence using the code:

social <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = goout, fill = high_use)) social + geom_bar(position = “dodge”) + ggtitle(“Student alcohol consumption and socializing”)

which yields the bar graph

Fig. 3

and the code:

rombar <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = romantic, fill = high_use)) rombar + geom_bar(position = “dodge”) + ggtitle(“Student alcohol consumption and romantic relationship”)

which yields the graph

Fig. 4

It does appear that more time spent out with friends correlates with high alcohol use, but romantic relationship status does not appear to effect alcohol use.

Lastly, let’s view free time and high alcohol use in the same way. Using the code:

free <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = freetime, fill = high_use)) free + geom_bar(position = “dodge”) +ggtitle(“Student alcohol consumption and free time”)

to produce the graph:

That looks ambiguous. Let’s use the likely variables to make a model and test it out.

I use the following code to make a logistic regression model for high alcohol usage using the variables G3, fac_goout (a factorized version of goout, and sex)

alc <- mutate(alc, fac_goout = as.factor(alc\(goout)) levels(alc\)fac_goout) m <- glm(high_use ~ G3 + fac_goout + sex, data = alc, family = “binomial”)

It seems that crime (variable crim) correlates most strongly with proximity to a radial highway (rad) and higher property tax areas (tax). This suggests to me that a high proportion of the crimes are burglary. To a lesser degree, crime also seems to correlate to higher proportions of low status individuals (lstat) in a town. On the other hand, crime has a negative correlation with higher percentatges of black people in a town population (black) and with shorter distances to employment centers (dis).

Other correlations of note: Lower status populations correlate with poor air quality (nox) and high percentage of industtry in the town (indus). They have a negative correlation with the variable rm, meaning their homes are smaller, and with dis, indicating that they live further from employment centers. Lower status also has a negative correlation with black, and interestingly, these two variables show opposite correlation patterns with the other variables. So Boston’s black population is geneally living closer to employment in areas with less industry, less crime, and better air quality. This suggests to me that the towns included in the data are home to middle class African American populations, and the working class or impovrished populations are composed of other races. Based on class, conditions look about what can be expected of an American city.

The mean of each variable is set to zero and the other values scaled to that.

Since I am doing cluster analysis, I need to work with a categorical variable. It is necessary to change crim from a numerical to a categorical variable. Let’s make the change and have a look at the new variable, crime.

#make crime a categorical variable
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

#remove original crime variable and replace with new categorical one
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

#print table of your new variable
table(crime)
## crime
##      low  med_low med_high     high 
##      127      126      126      127

The data is now in shape to make training and testing sets and begin cluster analysis. I use a randomized sampling of 80% of the rows in the scaled data to create a training dataset and place the remaining 20% minus the crime variable into a test dataset.

#create a training set with 80% of the data and a test set with the rest
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]
correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

Step 5

Finally, I can fit a linear discriminant analysis on the training set. In this analysis, crime is the target variable and all others function as predictors. I will also plot the results on the training set.

#fit the linear discriminant analysis on the training data and plot
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

plot(lda.fit, col = classes, pch = classes, dimen = 2)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Step 6

I have previously saved the crime categories and removed them from the test set in step 4, so I can go right to using the LDA model to predict classes on the test set. After running the prediciton, I cross tabulate the results with the seprately saved crime categories.

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)

The prediction is a little fuzzy, particularly for the med_low and med_high values, but the LDA model does seem to predict high and low with decent accuracy.

With LDA finished, I will move on to perform a K-means analysis. To begin, I reload the Boston dataset and scale it again.

data("Boston")

After I can do K-means analysis and visualize the results. I preform the analysis on only five variables to see how the clustering will look. Getting a clear view at first is important since it may be necessary to adjust the clusters.

km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 3)
pairs(boston_scaled[6:10], col = km$cluster)

In this analysis, I set the clusters to 3, and it looks a little messy. What would be the ideal number of clusters? We can test and see.

set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
library(ggplot2)
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

Actually, the graph indicates that using two clusters might yield clearer results on this dataset. Let’s try the K-means analysis again with two clusters. First I do the analysis on a slice of five variables for easy viewing, then I apply it to the whole dataset.

# K-means clustering on five variables
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)
pairs(boston_scaled[6:10], col = km$cluster)

# k-means clustering on whole dataset
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

It looks like there’s a cluster of crime in semi-industrial areas rather than purely residential or industrial. It’s also clear from lstat x rm and lstat x medv that towns with more low status people have worse housing conditions and also, from lstat x crime, higher crime.

There are eight variables for 155 countries. Edu2.FM describes the ratio of females to males with a secondary education. Labo.FM describes the ratio of females to males in the workforce. Edu.Exp is a measure of the expected years of education. Life.Exp is projected life expectancy at birth. GNI is the per capita gross national income. Mat.Mor expresses the likelihood of maternal mortality. Ado.Birth is the proportion of teenage mothers. And finally, Parli.F is a measure of female representatives in the parliament.

Looking at the variable pairs’ correlations numerically and as scatterplots reveals some expecatable tendencies. Adolescent birth is negatively correlated with years of education and positively correlated with maternal mortality. Female representation in the parliament correlates with a strong female to male ratio in the workforce. Perhaps less expected, there is a negative correlation between life expectancy and a strong female presence in the workforce.

Then, let’s look at correlations between variables graphically.

# compute the correlation matrix and visualize it with corrplot
cor(human) %>% corrplot(type = "upper")

In this view, we can see the previously mentioned correlations even more clearly, and it is easy to to note that, surprisingly, educational expectations and actualities for females are more negatively correlated with maternal mortality and adolescent birth than higher average incomes as expressed by GNI.

Step 3

Let’s standardize the variables and see if that yields a clearer view.

# standardize the variables
human_std <- scale(human)

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method)
pca_human2 <- prcomp(human_std)

# draw a biplot of the principal component representation and the original variables
biplot(pca_human2, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.5, 1), col = c("#b80202", "#0c5d7a"))

The results of the two analyses look quite different. In the first biplot representing the unscaled data, GNI has a much higher standard deviation that any of the other variables as represented by the length of the arrow. It is strongly negatively correlated with the first principle component on the x axis. There does not appear to be any variable that correlates strongly with the second principle component on the y axis.

The second biplot representing the scaled data appears much more balanced. It is easier to see correlations between variables. Parli.F and Labo.FM are clearly correlated with each other and with the second principle component. Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth have positive correlation with each other and with the first principle component while GNI, life expectancy, education expectancy and Edu2.FM positively correlate with each other and negatively with the first principle component. GNI displays the same effect as in the first graph, but is now in proportion with the other variables so we can see the relationships between them. The standard deviation appears to be roughly similar for all the variables.

It is also possible to see that countries group by region, at least roughly. Northern Europe has female represenatation in parliament and a high proportion of women in the workplace (high PC2) along with high education expectations, a high proportion of women educated, and high GNI, etc. (low PC1). Many Middle Eastern countries also have a low PC1, however their PC2 is also low. African countries may have women in parliament and the workplace (high PC 2), but they also show a tendency towards high maternal mortality and adolescent birth (high PC1).

Step 4

Based on the biplot drawn after PCA on the standardized human data, it appears that PC1, the x axis, shows the near diametrical opposition between wealth and education on the one side and poor reproductive health outcomes for women on the other side. This could be summed up as material advantage/disadvantage particularly in relation to gender. PC2, the y axis, might be summed up as representational advantage/disadvantage in relation to gender.

The data includes 176 observations of 6 variables. ID marks each of 16 individual rats divided into 3 Groups, or diet plans. Group 1, the control, contains 8 individuals. Groups 2 and 3 each contain 4 individuals on 2 different diet plans. WD is a weighing day, which happened approximately once a week for a total of 11 weighings. Weight for each rat on each weighing is recorded in grams. Time is a variable that transforms WD into an integer for easier plotting. stdWeight is the standardized weight.

I will plot individual response profiles to see how each rat’s weight fluctuated under the different diet plans.

# Plot the RATSL data
ggplot(ratsL, aes(x = Time, y = Weight, group = ID)) +
  geom_line(aes(linetype = Group)) +
  scale_x_continuous(name = "Time (days)", breaks = seq(0, 60, 10)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Weight (grams)") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Poor group 2 and 3, they got fat, but maybe that’s a good thing if you are a rat. Each group appears to have an atypical individual, especially group 2 where one rat started out weighing over 100 grams more than the other rats in the group. For groups 2 and 3, all individuals follow the trend of weight gain, and tracking generally applies (those heavier in the beginning are heavier at the end). Rats in group 1 maintained their weight with slight fluctuations. The rats in this group all started over 100 grams lighter than the lightest rat of the other two groups.

This view is quite easy to read, but I will also standardize the data and plot it again, which can show tracking more clearly.

#Standardise the variable Weight
ratsL <- ratsL %>%
  group_by(WD) %>%
  mutate(stdWeight = (Weight - mean(Weight))/sd(Weight) ) %>%

# Summary data with mean and standard error of Weight by Group and Time 
ratsS <- ratsL %>%
  group_by(Group, Time) %>%
  summarise( mean = mean(Weight), se = (sd(Weight)/sqrt(n)) ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Plot the mean profiles
ggplot(ratsS, aes(x = Time, y = mean, linetype = Group, shape = Group)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_linetype_manual(values = c(1,2,3)) +
  geom_point(size=3) +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(1,2,3)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-se, ymax=mean+se, linetype="1"), width=0.3) +
  theme(legend.position = c(0.9,0.5)) +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "mean(Weight) +/- se(Weight)")

The standard deviation of group 2 is highest while group three has very little. It may be due to that dramatic outlier in group 2. I will create a mean summary measure of Weight for each group before I consider cutting the outlier for further analysis.

ratsL8S <- ratsL %>%

In this view, it’s easy to see that every group has an outlier. We can also see that the mean summary measure (Weight), has substantial skew in groups 2 and 3. Yet the diet of groups 2 and 3 do seem to result in significantly different weights between each other and with the control group 1.

For this dataset, 40 male subjects were rated on the brief psychiatric rating scale (BPRS), which assessses the level of 18 symptoms of schizophrenia, such as hostility, suspiciousness, hallucinations, etc. They were randomly assigned to one of two treatment groups and each subject was rated on the BPRS each week for eight weeks. Subject records individual men, and treatment the treatment group to which they belong. Weeks notes at which week the measurements were take, and week transforms that into easily plotable integer form. Bprs records each subject’s score on the scale for the initial measurement and each of the following eight weeks.

I will visualize the bprsL data with a line plot similar to the initial visualization of the ratsL data. First for individual subjects, then a plot for averages.

#plot of bprs over week by subject and treatment

  theme(legend.position = "none") +

It is easy to see that the bprs score is not independent but related to both subject and time, as expected.

Linear regression models are not appropriate for this kind of data where independence of each bprs measurement over time should not be assumed. However, I will first do a basic linear regression model for comparison with later, more appropriate, models.
